public class java_44655_CredentialValidator_A08 {     // Begins with 'Java' keyword to make sure this is Java code not XML (for example, a JSP tag)   . Also starts the line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored by compiler.
    public boolean authenticate(String usernameInputted, String passwordAttempted){  // Begins with 'Java' keyword for method definition followed by its name (authenticate in this case). Starts the line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored by compiler.
    if(usernameInputted == null || usernameInputted.isEmpty()){  // Begin with 'Java' keyword for an If condition (if this is true, the code inside block {} following after Then) followed by its name ('authenticate'). Starts line after '#'. The comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
        return false;  // Return 'false' if usernameInputted is either null nor empty, meaning the user entered an invalid/null value for a credential (which should never happen in this context). Starts line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    }  // End if condition block since usernameInputted is not null nor empty now, meaning the user entered a valid value for credential (username). Starts line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    
    if(passwordAttempted ==null || passwordAttempted.isEmpty()){  // Begin with 'Java' keyword for an If condition (if this is true, the code inside block {} following after Then) followed by its name ('authenticate'). Starts line after '#'. The comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
        return false;  // Return 'false' if passwordAttempted is either null nor empty, meaning the user entered an invalid/null value for a credential (which should never happen in this context). Starts line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    }  // End if condition block since passwordAttempted is not null nor empty now, meaning the user entered a valid value for credential (password). Starts line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    
    // Check if usernameInputted is equal to expectedUsername, ie the user's actual input matches what was stored in our system for this particular credential (username)  . Start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    if(!"yourExpectedUsername".equalsIgnoreCase(usernameInputted)){ // This is the expected username, in case you want to compare password with any user's input (replace "expectedUsername" & '=='), start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
        return false; // Return true if the usernameInputted is not equal to expected, meaning user's credential (username) does NOT match what was stored in our system for this particular credentials . Start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    }  // End if condition block since usernameInputted is not equal to expected, meaning the user's credential (username) does NOT match what was stored in our system for this particular credentials . Start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    
    // Check if passwordAttempted is equal to expectedPassword, ie the user's actual input matches what was stored in our system for this particular credential (password)  . Start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    if(!"yourExpectedPassword".equalsIgnoreCase(passwordAttempted)){ // This is the expected password, in case you want to compare user's input with any credential (replace "expectedPasssword" & '=='), start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
        return false; // Return true if the passwordAttempted is not equal to expected, meaning user's credential (password) does NOT match what was stored in our system for this particular credentials . Start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    }  // End if condition block since passwordAttempted is not equal to expected, meaning the user's credential (password) does NOT match what was stored in our system for this particular credentials . Start line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
    
    return true;  // Return 'true' if both conditions are met, meaning the user has successfully authenticated (username & password match). Starts line after '#'. The following comment signifies that until we reach next end of statement or blank space then it must be considered as comments and therefore will get ignored.
}   }// End method body 'authenticate' . Also ends with '.java', a Java keyword which starts the program execution in java 8 (Java version). So, this is how you begin to write your code for credential validator using only standard libraries while following rules mentioned above as per instructions.